    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1069"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1069">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 344d62/26</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 4, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 3.40 p. m.</hi>] </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1395. Your 705, December 7.<note n="2" xml:id="d1069fn2">See preceding
                        footnote.</note> British Government answers that although August Piepenbrink
                    has declared intention of becoming American citizen he appears from a legal
                    standpoint to be still a German subject if he has not actually taken out letters
                    of naturalization and that in these circumstances it is not possible for him to
                    be released.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
